results.question: What is the user ID of the user, who was a subscriber when he created the list, who created a list for 10 consecutive years? If there are multiple users, indicate each of their user IDs.
results.evidence: user was a subscriber when he created the list refers to user_subscriber = 1; user who created a list for 10 consecutive years refers to user_id with list_creation_date_utc for 10 succeeding years;
results.ground_truth_sql: SELECT user_id FROM lists_users WHERE user_subscriber = 1 GROUP BY user_id HAVING MAX(SUBSTR(list_creation_date_utc, 1, 4)) - MIN(SUBSTR(list_creation_date_utc, 1, 4)) >= 10
results.generated_sql:
WITH YearlyLists AS (
    SELECT 
        `user_id`, 
        strftime('%Y', `list_creation_date_utc`) AS `year`, 
        COUNT(*) AS `list_count`
    FROM 
        `lists_users`
    WHERE 
        `user_subscriber` = 1
    GROUP BY 
        `user_id`, `year`
),
ConsecutiveYears AS (
    SELECT 
        `user_id`, 
        COUNT(DISTINCT `year`) AS `year_count`,
        MIN(`year`) AS `min_year`,
        MAX(`year`) AS `max_year`
    FROM 
        YearlyLists
    GROUP BY 
        `user_id`
    HAVING 
        `year_count` >= 10 AND 
        (CAST(`max_year` AS INTEGER) - CAST(`min_year` AS INTEGER) + 1) = 10
)
SELECT 
    DISTINCT `user_id`
FROM 
    ConsecutiveYears

results.question: How many users who created a list in the February of 2016 were eligible for trial when they created the list? Indicate the user id of the user who has the most number of followers in his list in February of 2016.
results.evidence: created a list in the February of 2016 refer to list_creation_date_utc BETWEEN 2/1/2016 and 2/29/2016; eligible for trial refers to user_eligible_for_trial = 1;
results.ground_truth_sql: SELECT T1.list_followers FROM lists AS T1 INNER JOIN lists_users AS T2 ON T1.user_id = T2.user_id AND T1.list_id = T2.list_id WHERE T2.list_creation_date_utc BETWEEN '2016-02-01' AND '2016-02-29' AND T2.user_eligible_for_trial = 1
results.generated_sql:
SELECT COUNT(DISTINCT LU.`user_id`) AS eligible_user_count, 
       L.`user_id` AS user_with_most_followers
FROM `lists` L
JOIN `lists_users` LU ON L.`list_id` = LU.`list_id`
JOIN `ratings_users` RU ON LU.`user_id` = RU.`user_id`
WHERE L.`list_creation_timestamp_utc` BETWEEN '2016-02-01' AND '2016-02-29'
  AND RU.`user_eligible_for_trial` = 1
GROUP BY L.`user_id`
ORDER BY L.`list_followers` DESC
LIMIT 1

results.question: What is the average popularity of each movie that was directed by Christopher Nolan? Indicate which movie directed by him has received the highest number of 5 rating scores.
results.evidence: 5 rating scores refer to rating_score; Christopher Nolan refer to director_name; average popularity of each movie refer to AVG(movie_popularity where director_name = 'Christopher Nolan')
results.ground_truth_sql: SELECT AVG(T2.movie_popularity) FROM ratings AS T1 INNER JOIN movies AS T2 ON T1.movie_id = T2.movie_id WHERE T2.director_name = 'Christopher Nolan'
results.generated_sql:
WITH NolanMovies AS (
    SELECT 
        `movie_id`, 
        `movie_title`, 
        AVG(`movie_popularity`) AS `average_popularity`
    FROM 
        `movies`
    WHERE 
        `director_name` = 'Christopher Nolan'
    GROUP BY 
        `movie_id`
),
RatingCounts AS (
    SELECT 
        `movie_id`, 
        COUNT(*) AS `five_star_count`
    FROM 
        `ratings`
    WHERE 
        `rating_score` = 5
    GROUP BY 
        `movie_id`
)
SELECT 
    NM.`movie_title`, 
    NM.`average_popularity`, 
    COALESCE(RC.`five_star_count`, 0) AS `five_star_count`
FROM 
    NolanMovies NM
LEFT JOIN 
    RatingCounts RC ON NM.`movie_id` = RC.`movie_id`
ORDER BY 
    RC.`five_star_count` DESC
LIMIT 1

results.question: Compute the average time in minute for each age group
results.evidence: teenager refers to 13 < age < = 19; adult refers to 19 < age < = 65; elder refers to age < = 65; highest average time per complaint = max(divide(sum(ser_time), count(ser_time)))
results.ground_truth_sql: SELECT CAST(SUM(CASE WHEN T1.age > 13 AND T1.age <= 19 THEN 60 * strftime('%H', ser_time) + strftime('%M', ser_time) + strftime('%S', ser_time) / 60 ELSE 0 END) AS REAL) / SUM(CASE WHEN T1.age > 13 AND T1.age <= 19 THEN 1 ELSE 0 END) AS teenagerAverageMins, CAST(SUM(CASE WHEN T1.age > 19 AND T1.age <= 65 THEN 60 * strftime('%H', ser_time) + strftime('%M', ser_time) + strftime('%S', ser_time) / 60 ELSE 0 END) AS REAL) / SUM(CASE WHEN T1.age > 19 AND T1.age <= 65 THEN 1 ELSE 0 END) AS adultAverageMins , CAST(SUM(CASE WHEN T1.age > 65 THEN 60 * strftime('%H', ser_time) + strftime('%M', ser_time) + strftime('%S', ser_time) / 60 ELSE 0 END) AS REAL) / SUM(CASE WHEN T1.age > 65 THEN 1 ELSE 0 END) AS elderAverageMins FROM client AS T1 INNER JOIN callcenterlogs AS T2 ON T1.client_id = T2.`rand client`
results.generated_sql:
SELECT 
    CASE 
        WHEN c.`age` > 13 AND c.`age` <= 19 THEN 'Teenager'
        WHEN c.`age` > 19 AND c.`age` <= 65 THEN 'Adult'
        WHEN c.`age` <= 65 THEN 'Elder'
    END AS `Age Group`,
    AVG(CAST(cl.`ser_time` AS REAL)) AS `Average Time (minutes)`
FROM 
    `client` c
JOIN 
    `callcenterlogs` cl ON c.`client_id` = cl.`rand client`
WHERE 
    c.`age` > 13 OR c.`age` <= 65
GROUP BY 
    `Age Group`

results.question: Provide the production companies of the movie that has over 35% average running time per movie in 2016.
results.evidence: production companies refers to company_name; in 2016 refers to release_date LIKE '2016%'; over 35% average running time per movie refers to divide(subtract(runtime, AVG(runtime)), AVG(runtime)) * 100 as percentage > 35
results.ground_truth_sql: SELECT T.company_name FROM ( SELECT DISTINCT T3.company_name, T1.runtime FROM movie AS T1 INNER JOIN movie_company AS T2 ON T1.movie_id = T2.movie_id INNER JOIN production_company AS T3 ON T3.company_id = T2.company_id WHERE T1.release_date LIKE '2016%' ) T WHERE T.runtime * 100 > (0.35 * ( SELECT AVG(T1.runtime) FROM movie AS T1 INNER JOIN movie_company AS T2 ON T1.movie_id = T2.movie_id INNER JOIN production_company AS T3 ON T3.company_id = T2.company_id WHERE T1.release_date LIKE '2016%' ) + ( SELECT AVG(T1.runtime) FROM movie AS T1 INNER JOIN movie_company AS T2 ON T1.movie_id = T2.movie_id INNER JOIN production_company AS T3 ON T3.company_id = T2.company_id WHERE T1.release_date LIKE '2016%' )) * 100
results.generated_sql:
SELECT DISTINCT PC.`company_name`
FROM `movie` M
JOIN `movie_company` MC ON M.`movie_id` = MC.`movie_id`
JOIN `production_company` PC ON MC.`company_id` = PC.`company_id`
WHERE M.`release_date` LIKE '2016%'
AND (M.`runtime` - (SELECT AVG(`runtime`) FROM `movie`)) / (SELECT AVG(`runtime`) FROM `movie`) > 0.35

        T.`direction`

    WHERE

LoadShapeCounts AS (

results.ground_truth_sql: SELECT T3.Name FROM movie AS T1 INNER JOIN characters AS T2 ON T1.MovieID = T2.MovieID INNER JOIN actor AS T3 ON T3.ActorID = T2.ActorID WHERE T3.Gender = 'Female' AND T1.Title = 'Godzilla' AND T3.`Birth City` = 'Sherman Oaks' AND T3.`Height (Inches)` * 100 > ( SELECT AVG(`Height (Inches)`) FROM actor ) * 50
results.generated_sql:
SELECT C.`Character Name`
FROM `actor` A
JOIN `characters` C ON A.`ActorID` = C.`ActorID`
JOIN `movie` M ON C.`MovieID` = M.`MovieID`
WHERE A.`Gender` = 'Female'
  AND A.`Birth City` = 'Sherman Oaks'
  AND A.`Height (Inches)` > (SELECT AVG(`Height (Inches)`) * 0.5 FROM `actor`)
  AND M.`Title` = 'Bruce Almighty'

results.question: Calculate the GPA of the semester for Laughton Antonio.
results.evidence: GPA of the semester = DIVIDE(SUM(MULTIPLY(credit, grade)), SUM(credit)); grade 'A' refers to gpa = 4; grade 'B' refers to gpa = 3; grade 'C' refers to gpa = 2; grade 'D' refers to gpa = 1;

FROM 
    student s
JOIN 
    registration r ON s.`student_id` = r.`student_id`
JOIN

results.question: What is the difference in the average GPA of students who took the hardest and easiest courses?
results.evidence: difference in the average gpa = SUBTRACT(AVG(gpa WHERE MAX(diff)), AVG(gpa where min(diff))); difficulty of the course refers to diff; hardest course refers to MAX(diff); easiest course refers to MIN(diff);
results.ground_truth_sql: SELECT AVG(T1.gpa) FROM student AS T1 INNER JOIN registration AS T2 ON T1.student_id = T2.student_id INNER JOIN course AS T3 ON T2.course_id = T3.course_id WHERE T3.diff IN (2, 1) GROUP BY T3.diff
results.generated_sql:
SELECT 
    (SELECT AVG(s.`gpa`) 
     FROM `student` s 
     JOIN `registration` r ON s.`student_id` = r.`student_id` 
     JOIN `course` c ON r.`course_id` = c.`course_id` 
     WHERE c.`diff` = (SELECT MAX(`diff`) FROM `course`)) - 
    (SELECT AVG(s.`gpa`) 
     FROM `student` s 
     JOIN `registration` r ON s.`student_id` = r.`student_id` 
     JOIN `course` c ON r.`course_id` = c.`course_id` 
     WHERE c.`diff` = (SELECT MIN(`diff`) FROM `course`)) AS `gpa_difference`

results.question: What is the ratio of good to bad business star for a businesses that are opened all the time?
results.evidence: opened all the time refers to Business_Hours where day_id BETWEEN 1 and 7 and opening_time = closing_time; ratio can be computed as DIVIDE(COUNT(stars BETWEEN 3.5 and 5), COUNT(stars BETWEEN 1 and 2.5));
results.ground_truth_sql: SELECT CAST(SUM(CASE WHEN T1.stars BETWEEN 3.5 AND 5 THEN 1 ELSE 0 END) AS REAL) / SUM(CASE WHEN T1.stars BETWEEN 1 AND 2.5 THEN 1 ELSE 0 END) AS ratio FROM Business AS T1 INNER JOIN Business_Hours AS T2 ON T1.business_id = T2.business_id
results.generated_sql: SELECT CAST(COUNT(CASE WHEN B.`stars` BETWEEN 3.5 AND 5 THEN 1 END) AS FLOAT) / NULLIF(COUNT(CASE WHEN B.`stars` BETWEEN 1 AND 2.5 THEN 1 END), 0) AS `good_to_bad_ratio` FROM `Business` B WHERE B.`business_id` IN (SELECT BH.`business_id` FROM `Business_Hours` BH WHERE BH.`day_id` BETWEEN 1 AND 7 GROUP BY BH.`business_id` HAVING COUNT(CASE WHEN BH.`opening_time` = BH.`closing_time` THEN 1 END) = 7)

results.question: List out 10 business ID that are being reviewed the most by users and list out what are top 3 business categories.
results.evidence: being reviewed the most refers to MAX(user_id); business categories refer to category_name;
results.ground_truth_sql: SELECT T2.business_id, T3.category_name FROM Reviews AS T1 INNER JOIN Business_categories AS T2 ON T1.business_id = T2.business_id INNER JOIN Categories AS T3 ON T2.category_id = T3.category_id GROUP BY T2.business_id ORDER BY COUNT(T1.user_id) DESC LIMIT 10
results.generated_sql: SELECT R.`business_id`, C.`category_name` FROM (SELECT `business_id`, COUNT(`user_id`) AS review_count FROM `Reviews` GROUP BY `business_id` ORDER BY review_count DESC LIMIT 10) AS R JOIN `Business_Categories` AS BC ON R.`business_id` = BC.`business_id` JOIN `Categories` AS C ON BC.`category_id` = C.`category_id` GROUP BY R.`business_id`, C.`category_name` ORDER BY R.`business_id`, COUNT(C.`category_name`) DESC LIMIT 3
